fields.title: YOU ASK, WE ANSWER
fields.description: You'll find many of our most commonly asked questions here, but if you'd like to ask something more specific, contact us directly.

fields.question: Which products contain milk ingredients?
fields.answer: We have three products containing milk ingredients: Mission® Cheddar Cheese Flavored Dip, Mission® Salsa con Queso, and Mission® Guacamole Flavored Dip.

fields.question: What does the date printed on the package mean?
fields.answer: This date is the last day we guarantee our products to meet our high standards for taste and quality.

fields.question: What does this information printed on the package mean: RC MAR 29 14 L1 03:42?
fields.answer: It is the code date we use to identify the plant that produced the product, the expiration date of the product, and the production line and time. This information helps us for traceability purposes.

fields.question: Do any of your products contain any of the major eight allergen foods?
fields.answer: Yes. All wheat flour tortillas and wraps contain wheat. Mission® products do not contain any of the following ingredients: peanuts, crustacean, fish, or tree nuts. Ingredients for each product can be found on the Products page (click on desired product for nutrition information).

fields.question: Which products contain milk ingredients?
fields.answer: We have three products containing milk ingredients: Mission® Cheddar Cheese Flavored Dip, and Mission® Salsa con Queso.

fields.question: Are Mission products gluten free?
fields.answer: Mission® corn products are produced with 100% corn masa flour; wheat ingredients are not added to the formulation. These products include corn tortillas, corn tortilla chips, taco shells, and tostadas. These products are produced in plants that also process wheat tortillas.

fields.question: Is there any wheat, rye, barley, or oats in corn tortillas?
fields.answer: No. Mission corn tortillas do not contain wheat, rye, barley, or oat ingredients.

fields.question: Are wheat flour tortillas produced in the same lines as corn products?
fields.answer: No, our corn production lines are dedicated to corn products only. Wheat flour tortillas are produced on dedicated lines.

fields.question: Is wheat used in any way to make the corn products?
fields.answer: There are no wheat ingredients or incidental wheat present in the products or on the lines that produce corn products.

fields.question: Is there a potential for cross-contamination of corn products with wheat ingredients?
fields.answer: All Mission plants have strict food safety programs in place, including a very comprehensive Allergen Control Program.

fields.question: Does Mission use Monosodium Glutamate (MSG) in their products?
fields.answer: There is MSG in the following products: Mission Cheddar Cheese Flavored Dip, Mission Salsa con Queso, and Mission Chicharrones.

fields.question: Do any Mission products contain ingredients from animal sources?
fields.answer: The only products that are animal-derived are Mission® Cheddar Cheese Flavored Dip, Mission® Salsa con Queso, and Mission® Chicharrones.

fields.question: What is the source of mono- and diglycerides listed on the ingredients of flour tortillas?
fields.answer: They are vegetable-based.

fields.question: Why does Mission use preservatives?
fields.answer: Preservatives help protect the flavor and the freshness of our products. We use only the minimum amount of preservatives necessary to deliver a quality product with the necessary shelf life.

fields.question: Does Mission use partially hydrogenated oils?
fields.answer:
Partially hydrogenated oil is not used as a primary oil in the products manufactured by Mission. It may be present in some specialty formulas or as a subcomponent in an ingredient used in specific formulas. If partially hydrogenated oil is present in a formula, it will be declared as such in the ingredient statement.

Mission flour tortillas declare 0g trans fats on the packaging and the ingredients list “hydrogenated oil”. Is it really 0g trans fats?

Food manufacturers are allowed to list the amount of trans fat with less than 0.5 grams (½g) as 0 (zero) on the nutrition facts panel. As a result, consumers may see a few products that list 0 grams trans fat on the label, while the ingredient list will have “shortening”, “partially hydrogenated vegetable oil”, or “hydrogenated vegetable oil” listed. This means the food contains very small amounts (less than 0.5g) of trans fat per serving. (Reference: FDA FAQ).

In order to produce wheat flour tortillas and wraps with 0 grams of trans fats, we at Mission® use a blend of fully hydrogenated soybean oil plus soybean oil, which allows us to label products with 0 grams of trans fats per serving.

fields.question: Are Mission products kosher?
fields.answer: Most of our products are kosher. Look for the kosher symbol on our packaging. The following products are kosher: Mission corn tortillas, Mission flour tortillas, Mission wraps, Mission taco shells, and Mission tortilla chips. The following products are not kosher: Mission Chicharrones, Mission salsas and dips, and taco shell dinner kits.

fields.question: Is it possible for a food product to list the amount of trans fat as 0g on the Nutrition Fact panel if the ingredient list indicates that it contains "partially hydrogenated vegetable oil"?
fields.answer: Yes. Food manufacturers are allowed to list the amount of trans fat with less than 0.5 grams (½g) as 0 (zero) on the nutrition facts panel. As a result, consumers may see a few products that list 0 grams trans fat on the label, while the ingredient list will have “shortening”, “partially hydrogenated vegetable oil”, or “hydrogenated vegetable oil” listed. This means the food contains very small amounts (less than 0.5g) of trans fat per serving. (Reference: FDA FAQ).

fields.question: Where can I find nutritional information for Mission products?
fields.answer: For nutrition facts and ingredients, please visit the Products page and click on the desired product for nutrition information.

fields.question: Is Mission packaging recyclable?
fields.answer: Yes, most packaging is recyclable. Most of the plastic bags used for Mission corn and flour tortillas and wraps are recyclable #4.

fields.question: What is the difference between a wrap and a flour tortilla?
fields.answer: Wraps are a sandwich with a twist; they are typically larger than a regular flour tortilla and come in a variety of flavors. Good for appetizers and party snacks.

fields.question: What is the difference between a burrito, soft taco, and fajita size tortilla?
fields.answer: The difference is only in the diameter. A burrito is approximately 10”, a soft taco is about 8,” and the fajita is about 6”.

fields.question: Can I get recipes by mail?
fields.answer: No, we are sorry, we currently do not have recipes available by mail.

fields.question: What is the shelf life of Mission products?
fields.answer:
The shelf life of Mission® products varies depending on their formulation and storage conditions. The following is the typical shelf life of Mission® products stored at ambient temperature (unopened package): Flour tortillas: 16 - 45 days*; Wraps: 60 days; Corn tortillas: 25 - 45 days*; Tortilla chips: 60 days; Taco shells: 180 days; Tostadas: 60 days; Chicharrones: 90 days; Cheddar Cheese Flavored Dip and Salsa con Queso: 9 months; Chunky salsas: 12 months; Guacamole Flavored Dip: 15 months.

* For selected markets, the product is kept refrigerated at all times. Under these conditions, the shelf life of flour and corn tortillas is 60 - 90 days.

fields.question: How long can tortillas be kept at ambient temperature after I buy them?
fields.answer: The tortillas can be left at ambient temperature and should be good until the date printed on the package.

fields.question: I bought a package of tortillas and they were not refrigerated at the store. Should I refrigerate them at home?
fields.answer: Not necessarily. The tortillas will last at ambient temperature until the date printed on the package. If they are placed in the refrigerator until they are ready to be used, they will last longer. The shelf life in the refrigerator varies depending on the conditions the product was stored in prior to placing them in a refrigerated container.

fields.question: I bought a package of tortillas and they were in the refrigerated section at the store. Should I refrigerate them at home?
fields.answer: Yes. If the product was in the refrigerated section at the store, they have a refrigerated code date printed on the package. If the product is not kept in the refrigerator after purchase, it may grow mold before its expiration date, depending on humidity and other ambient factors.

fields.question: How long can we keep the tortillas after opening the package?
fields.answer: It depends on the handling conditions the product was exposed to. If you are not going to consume the whole package after opening it, wash your hands, remove the tortillas you will need, and tightly close the package. The product should be good until the expiration date printed on the package.

fields.question: What happens to tortillas after their shelf life has expired?
fields.answer: They may grow mold and become dry.

fields.question: Is it okay to freeze corn tortillas?
fields.answer: Yes, it is okay to freeze corn tortillas. It is very important that you let them thaw in the refrigerator for a day or two before using them. Corn tortillas should not be thawed in the microwave.

fields.question: Is it okay to freeze flour tortillas?
fields.answer: Yes, it is okay to freeze flour tortillas. It is very important that you let them thaw in the refrigerator for a day or two before using them. Flour tortillas should not be thawed in the microwave.

fields.question: Are Mission products Vegan and Vegetarian?
fields.answer: We do not use any animal derived ingredients in any of our tortilla products, making them vegetarian and vegan friendly.

fields.question: Are Mission products GMO?
fields.answer: We currently have both GMO and Non-GMO products. The labeling on the package will say Organic and state Non-GMO.  If the product packaging does not say Organic or Non-GMO, then the product may be one of the GMO products.

fields.question: Are tortillas safe to eat after the date printed on them?
fields.answer: The date stamped on the package is the date that we can guarantee freshness of the product. If you choose to consume the product any time after that date we ask that you use your best judgment based on the appearance, texture, taste, and smell.

fields.question: Why is there a Scavenger packet in the tortillas?
fields.answer: The green packet inside Organic tortillas is an oxygen absorber to maintain freshness of the product.

fields.question: How do you heat up a tortilla?
fields.answer:
Tortillas may be heated on a skillet or electric griddle, on the grill, or in the microwave. 

For best results, heat tortillas on an ungreased skillet over medium-high heat for 10 to 15 seconds. Flip and heat for another 5 to 10 seconds. 

If you're using a microwave, place 4 to 6 tortillas between two damp paper towels. Microwave 30 to 45 seconds or until heated through. Wrap in a cloth or tortilla warmer until ready to serve.

fields.question: Do you send out coupons?
fields.answer: Unfortunately, we do not have any coupons available to mail out. Periodically, coupons are distributed in select Sunday newspapers.

fields.question: How do you calculate calories?
fields.answer:
Calories may be calculated in different ways. We recently transitioned calorie calculation from method A to B, and since these products contain a high level of fiber, the calorie value decreases significantly.

A. CALORIES = FAT x 9 + PROTEIN x 4 + TOTAL CARB X 4

B. CALORIES = FAT x 9 + PROTEIN x 4 + (TOTAL CARB - TOTAL DIETARY FIBER) X 4 + SOLUBLE FIBER X 2

fields.question: Why the recent packaging change with Low Carb tortillas?
fields.answer: We have recently made a change with all our Mission Carb Balance tortillas. The ingredients in the product formula remain the same as before. However, we changed the amount of ingredients used and had to update product packaging based on a new FDA regulation pertaining to how nutritional information in calculated.

fields.title: Supply Chain Transparency
fields.subtitle: Supply Chain Transparency: California SB 657
fields.content:
Effective January 1, 2012, the California Transparency in Supply Chains Act of 2010 (SB 657) will require large manufacturers and retailers that sell goods in California to make certain disclosures regarding their efforts to address slavery and human trafficking. The Act is intended to ensure that retail manufactures and sellers are disclosing their efforts to eradicate slavery and human trafficking from their supply chains.

 

Gruma Corporation dba Mission Foods is committed to observing high ethical standards in the conduct of its business. We are committed to the goals of SB 657 and are committed to compliance with all laws and regulations governing efforts to address slavery and human trafficking. In establishing and maintaining relationships with our suppliers, we ask them to be committed to the same high ethical standards, and that they are not linked to activities that would be considered abusive or exploitive, including human trafficking and slavery.

 

Mission Foods does engage in verification of our product supply chain to ensure compliance with laws governing slavery and human trafficking. These verifications do not currently include a certification regarding the materials used in manufacture by each supplier, and do not include use of a third party.

 

Mission Foods does conduct extensive audits of its suppliers for food safety, and hence many issues related to safety of workers and their human rights can be discovered and addressed. Mission Foods also retains third party auditors for most international suppliers. Principally, Mission Foods employs the services of the American Institute of Baking. The American Institute of Baking conducts unannounced food safety audits at the Mission Foods manufacturing facilities located in the United States.

 

Mission Foods has a rigorous internal accountability system for its suppliers. Suppliers are required to submit detailed information on the materials incorporated in the products they sell Mission Foods. The materials certifications must include material subcomponents, and raw materials, with all country of origin information and sources detailed. For any raw material or component sourced in China, Mission Foods requires submittal of a third party audit of the Chinese supplier facility.

 

As part of its internal accountability system to ensure compliance with all laws and regulations, Mission Foods can take action upon discovery of violations, including requesting a prompt redress of alleged violations, and corrective actions, as well as the potential for termination of the supplier relationship in the event of violations or failure to adequately remedy violations.

 

Mission Foods has a robust employee training program that is currently being revised to include training on how to minimize the potential risk of slavery and human trafficking in the supply chain.

fields.title: Humble Beginnings
fields.intro_text: Mission is a proud subsidiary of Gruma Corporation, which began in 1949. Gruma is the leading tortilla manufacturer worldwide, delivering the authentic Mexican flavors you know and love from Mission.

fields.title: GRUMA was Founded
fields.description: GRUMA was founded in Cerralvo, Nuevo Leon, Mexico by Mr. Roberto González Gutiérrez and his son Mr. Roberto González Barrera with the MASECA brand that derives from the concepts of “Masa Seca” (dry dough), i.e., dehydrated corn flour.

fields.title: Solving Preservation Challenges
fields.description: GRUMA means GRUPO MASECA. The company´s inception solved the problem of preserving the “nixtamal” dough for the preparation of tortillas, Mexican´s staple food.

fields.title: Expanding Operations
fields.description: After expanding operations in Mexico with seven corn flour mills in the 1960s, our internationalization began in 1973 when GRUMA started operations in Costa Rica with the production and marketing of packaged tortillas.

fields.title: The Mission Brand
fields.description: The old MISSION Tortilla Factory was a key acquisition in the United States. Its brand name and image became one of the GRUMA´s most recognized insignias worldwide. The United States represented another big challenge for GRUMA since it was a new market with many possibilities for appealing to Latino and non-Latino populations.

fields.title: Founding TECNOMAIZ
fields.description: At the same time, a new business was growing and with proprietary technology, our affiliate TECNOMAIZ was founded, specializing in the manufacturing and marketing of tortilla production lines with varying capacities.

fields.title: US Expansion
fields.description: As part of our continued expansion strategy into international markets in the 80's, we acquired 10 plants in the US, built the first corn flour mill in Edinburg, Texas which created AZTECA MILLING, and acquired GUERRERO, a brand with strong roots in Southern California, especially with the Hispanic market.

fields.title: Olympic Boulevard Mega-Plant
fields.description: With a clear vision, we built our MISSION tortilla mega-plant on Olympic Boulevard in Los Angeles, California, US.

fields.title: GRUMA Goes Public
fields.description: We made our initial public offering of GRUMA shares on the Mexican Stock Exchange.

fields.title: Rancho Cucamonga
fields.description: We built Rancho Cucamonga, in Los Angeles, California - surpassing the Olympic plant’s production - and producing 25 million tortillas per day.

fields.title: New York Stock Exchange
fields.description: GRUMA´s shares were listed on the New York Stock Exchange.

fields.title: European Expansion
fields.description: The United Kingdom became the spearhead for entering into the European market, with its success resulting in increased business for MISSION FOODS in Europe.

fields.title: European Factory Openings
fields.description: We opened our first tortilla facility in Coventry, England and thanks to the success achieved, we decided to increase our business in Europe and acquired a wheat tortilla factory in Holland and a corn flour mill in Ceggia, near Venice, Italy.

fields.title: Strengthened Share of Value
fields.description: GRUMA entered the Asian market, acquired a new plant in Melbourne, Australia and strengthened our share of value – added products, both locally and globally.

fields.title: GRUMA Enters the Asian Market
fields.description: GRUMA entered the Asian market by building a MISSION FOODS tortilla factory in Shanghai China in 2006.

fields.title: Continued Growth
fields.description: GRUMA bought Rositas Investment Company, acquired a plant in Melbourne Australia, Oz – Mex and purchased a plant specializing in flatbreads in Malaysia, strengthening its share of value added products both locally and globally and becoming one of the first Mexican companies with presence in Asia and Oceania.

fields.title: Shanghai Plant Opens
fields.description: We opened the purpose built Shanghai plant. MISSION FOODS began its journey into Asia by launching a range of food service products including flour & corn tortillas, corn chips and pizza bases.

fields.title: Celebrating 60 Years
fields.description: We proudly celebrated 60 years of operations in 2009 and opened a new MISSION FOODS facility in Melbourne Australia and through innovation and use of new technologies strengthened our global presence.

fields.title: US, Russia, and Turkey Expansion
fields.description: There were acquisitions in the United States, Russia and Turkey, forging our expansion globally.

fields.title: International Mission Brand Launch
fields.description: With great success, we launched the MISSION brand in Singapore and Malaysia.

fields.title: Mission Wraps in Everyday Chinese Cuisine
fields.description: MISSION FOODS launches into the China Retail environment with a range of four Wraps and an intensive communications campaign to begin building awareness of the MISSION brand and how to use Wraps in everyday Chinese cuisine.

fields.title: Award Recognition
fields.description: In Washington, Juan González Moreno, Chairman of the Board and Chief Executive Officer of GRUMA, receives the "Good Neighbor-2013" award granted by the United States Chamber of Commerce. "Is a great pride for me to receive this award, and it is more because my father, Don Roberto González Barrera, received it 15 years ago," said the Executive. The award was presented in recognition of the vision and engagement that has helped GRUMA strengthen commercial relations between Mexico and United States for more than 35 years.

fields.title: Malaysia's Longest Wrap
fields.description: GRUMA makes history in the Malaysian Guinness Book of Records by creating Malaysia´s Longest Wrap, reaching a length of 248 meters. The initiative involves more the than 1,500 Malaysian consumers.

fields.title: Expanded Retail Footprint
fields.description: MISSION FOODS expands its footprint in retail and launches a range of corn chips in unique flavors bringing to Chinese consumers a favorite snack made popular in the West.

fields.title: Mission in Moscow
fields.description: GRUMA further expands its footprint by announcing the purchase of MEXIFOODS Company in Spain and Mr. Juan González Moreno places the first stone of the new tortilla factory of MISSION in Moscow.

fields.title: Azteca Foods Europe Acquisition
fields.description: On March 31, through its Spanish subsidiary GRUMA International Foods, GRUMA entered into a purchase-sale contract with US companies Fat Taco, S.L. and Azteca Foods Inc., to acquire “Azteca Foods Europe”, the company representing their tortilla, wraps, tortilla chips, prepared foods and salsas production and commercialization operations in Europe. Azteca Foods Europe has a modern plant in Spain, and its products mainly go to the hotel, restaurant, and supermarket chain segments. Their products were sold in more than 19 countries in Europe, as well as in the Middle East and northern Africa, including the United Arab Emirates, Israel, Kuwait, Turkey, and Algeria, among others.

fields.title: The Mission Foods Texas-Mexico Center
fields.description: In April, GRUMA president and CEO, Juan González Moreno and the president of the Southern Methodist University of Texas in Dallas (SMU), Gerald Turner, signed an agreement to create The Mission Foods Texas-Mexico Center. Its main purpose consists in studying, elevating, and improving Mexico-Texas-United States relations with investigations, annual conferences, and public forums. GRUMA-Mission Foods contributed $4 million to the project.

fields.title: Addition of Folic Acid to Corn Flour
fields.description: Seeking to benefit the Mexican and Hispanic populations in the United States, the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approved the addition of folic acid to corn flour to reduce the number of fetal spinal malformations, better known as spina bifida. This is the most important accomplishment in the history of Latino nutrition in the United States, and was made possible thanks to joint work carried out since 2012 by GRUMA and the following civil associations: Spina Bifida Associations, American Academy of Pediatrics, National

fields.title: Consolidated Mission Foods Presence
fields.description: GRUMA consolidated MISSION FOODS presence in Mexico by announcing the construction of the third tortilla and snack plant in the country.

fields.title: Mission Foods Russia Factory
fields.description: GRUMA announces the foundation of a US50mdd and state-of-the-art tortilla and snack MISSION FOODS factory in Russia.

fields.description: MISSION FOODS Asia announced tortilla and snacks E-commerce through Alibaba, in China

fields.description: MISSION FOODS US sent 26 tons of products to those affected by Hurricane “Harvey” in Houston, Texas.

fields.top_paragraphs:
Our award-winning Mission® Green program helps us ensure that our products and processes have as small an impact on the environment as possible.That includes utilizing alternative energy sources and reducing waste materials from our packaging.

 

Through Mission® Green, we strive to increase energy consumption from renewable sources by 20% in 5 years, reduce emissions by 10% in 5 years, and recycle 50% of waste generated in 5 years.
